04675nam a22006135i 9780520940901DE-B159720200424112023.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||200424t20042004cau    fo  d z      eng d  a97805209409017 a10.1525/97805209409012doi  a(DE-B1597)520472  a(OCoLC)56733733  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  acaucUS-CA 4aJC421b.S32 2004eb 7aPOL0100002bisacsh04a321.82221 aSamons, Loren J., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aWhat's Wrong with Democracy? :bFrom Athenian Practice to American Worship /cLoren J. Samons. 1aBerkeley, CA : bUniversity of California Press, c[2004] 4cÂ©2004  a1 online resource (327 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tMaps And Illustrations -- tPreface -- tAbbreviations -- tIntroduction -- t1. Athenian Society And Government -- t2. Democracy And Demagogues: Election, Voting, And Qualifications For Citizenship -- t3. Public Finance: Democracy And The People'S Purse -- t4. Foreign Policy I: Democracy Imperial -- t5. Foreign Policy II: The Peloponnesian War -- t6. National Defense: Democracy Defeated -- t7. Democracy And Religion -- tConclusion: Socrates, Pericles, And The Citizen -- tNotes -- tSelect Bibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aFifth-century Athens is praised as the cradle of democracy and sometimes treated as a potential model for modern political theory or practice. In this daring reassessment of classical Athenian democracy and its significance for the United States today, Loren J. Samons provides ample justification for our founding fathers' distrust of democracy, a form of government they scorned precisely because of their familiarity with classical Athens. How Americans have come to embrace "democracy" in its modern form-and what the positive and negative effects have been-is an important story for all contemporary citizens. Confronting head-on many of the beliefs we hold dear but seldom question, Samons examines Athens's history in the fifth and fourth centuries B.C. in order to test the popular idea that majority rule leads to good government. Challenging many basic assumptions about the character and success of Athenian democracy, What's Wrong with Democracy? offers fascinating and accessible discussions of topics including the dangers of the popular vote, Athens's acquisitive foreign policy, the tendency of the state to overspend, the place of religion in Athenian society, and more. Sure to generate controversy, Samons's bold and iconoclastic book finds that democracy has begun to function like an unacknowledged religion in our culture, immune from criticism and dissent, and he asks that we remember the Athenian example and begin to question our uncritical worship of democratic values such as freedom, choice, and diversity.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2020) 0aDemocracyxHistory. 0aDirect democracyxGreecexAthens. 0aDirect democracyzGreecezAthens. 0aPolitical culturexHistoryxUnited States. 0aPolitical culturezUnited StatesxHistory. 0aRepresentative government and representationxUnited States. 0aRepresentative government and representationzUnited States. 0aRepublicanismxHistoryxUnited States. 0aRepublicanismzUnited StatesxHistory. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / History & Theory.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUC Press eBook Package 2000-2015z978311066334108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUC Press eBook Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311069042240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520940901423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780520940901.jpg  a978-3-11-066334-1  UC Press eBook Package 2000-2015c2000d2015  a978-3-11-069042-2  UC Press